4, 1826 |sessionend3 = March 3, 1827 |previous = 18th |next = 20th }} The
'Nineteenth United States Congress' was a meeting of the legislative branch of
the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and
the United States House of Representatives. It met in Washington, D.C. from
March 4, 1825 to March 4, 1827, during the first two years of the administration
of U.S. President John Quincy Adams. The apportionment of seats in the House of
Representatives was based on the Fourth Census of the United States in 1820. The
Senate had a majority of Jackson Men, while the House had an Anti-Jackson (pro-
Adams) majority.
